      <p>
       <span class="label label-default">
        #13
       </span>
       <span class="label label-danger">
        Miguel Grinberg
       </span>
       said
       <span class="flask-moment" data-format="fromNow(0)" data-refresh="0" data-timestamp="2013-02-23T17:53:26Z">
        2013-02-23T17:53:26Z
       </span>
      </p>
      <div style="overflow: auto;">
       <p style="white-space: pre-wrap;">
        @Robert: No, not really.What you are trying to do is to combine different entities in a single table. You can do that, but not with references. Let's simplify your example and consider just buildings and units. To have both in a single table you have to have the data for the building and the data for the unit all as columns of one table. The problem with this approach is that if you have a building that has 20 units you have to duplicate the building information in 20 rows, where each row varies just in the unit information. Even if you agree to do that, consider what would happen when you need to update one of the columns that describe the building, let's say the address. You would need to go update 20 rows in the database with the same change! So this isn't an approach that scale well, if you have a buildings table and a units table and you make relationship between them the same data can be represented without duplication. I hope this helps!
       </p>
      </div>
     </div>
    </li>
